# Module: feature-registry

Records the user-visible stories of **{{ project_name }}** and traces each to its
acceptance criteria and tests. Runs in CI via `process-gates` and locally via
`python scripts/process/check_feature_registry.py`.

## When a story is required

Mandatory rule *"tests prove acceptance"* (`docs/process/mandatory-rules.md`)
routes here: any user-visible behaviour, UI flow, contract, or test-coverage
change needs an affected story **before** implementation. New behaviour gets a
new story first. This is where a scenario sharpened at onboarding — including a
cross-repo coupling — is deposited as a concrete requirement.

## One story per file

Create `docs/process/feature-registry/STORY-NNNN.json` (one file per story so
stories diff and merge independently):

- **id** — `STORY-NNNN` (four digits), unique across the registry.
- **title** — a short label.
- **story** — one sentence in EARS form: *As a `<role>`, when `<trigger>`, the
  system shall `<response>`.* Wording is graded by humans, not the gate.
- **acceptance** — a non-empty list of `{id, text}`; each `text` is a gradeable,
  testable statement.
- **status** — `proposed | in-progress | done | deprecated`.
- **tests** — paths (optionally with a `::node` selector) to the tests that
  prove the acceptance. `status: done` needs at least one.
- **adr** (optional) — `ADR-NNNN` linking a decision under `docs/process/adr/`.
- **blocked_by** (optional) — a list of `STORY-NNNN` ids this story depends on
  (sequencing, not decomposition). Absent or `[]` means no dependency.
- **parent** (optional) — one `STORY-NNNN` this story decomposes (an epic → its
  tasks; a tree, not sequencing). Absent or `null` means no parent. A child
  carries its own delta and *references* the parent — it does not copy the
  parent's context.
- **issue**, **links** (optional) — forward-compat slots for the GitHub-Issues
  and contracts modules; stored but not yet enforced.

Copy `STORY-0001.example.json` (shipped, inert) as a starting point.

## Dependencies and ready-to-start order

`blocked_by` records that one story must land before another. The gate keeps the
dependency graph honest; a read-only tool turns it into a work order.

- **Hard (CI fails):** a `blocked_by` that is not a list of `STORY-NNNN`; a ref
  to a story that does not exist (dangling); a story listing **itself**; a
  **dependency cycle** (reported with its path — an unbuildable order).
- **Best-effort:** a `done` story whose blocker is not itself `done` — a note
  that the order looks off, never a block (status can move out of order during a
  migration).
- `python scripts/process/story_order.py` (read-only, never a gate) prints the
  **ready-to-start** stories (no unfinished blockers), the **blocked** ones with
  what they wait on, and a suggested topological order.

`blocked_by` is sequencing between siblings; it is not parent/child
decomposition. Rendering the dependency into a GitHub issue as "Blocked by #N"
is an optional projection — see the `github-issues` module — never the source of
truth, which stays here in the registry.

## Decomposition (parent/child)

`parent` records that a story is part of an epic. It is a **tree** — one parent
per child — and orthogonal to `blocked_by` (an epic's children need not block
each other).

- **Hard:** a `parent` that is not `STORY-NNNN`; a ref to a non-existent story
  (dangling); a story that is its own parent; a **parent cycle**.
- **Best-effort:** a parent that is `done` while a child is not (an epic cannot
  outrun its parts); a child whose `title`/`story` is byte-identical to its
  parent's (carry the delta, not a copy — only verbatim duplication is
  mechanically detectable; the rest is review discipline).
- An **epic** (a story that is some other story's `parent`) may be `done`
  without its own test **only when all its children are `done`** — their
  (leaf-enforced) tests then genuinely cover it (a note). A done epic with an
  unfinished child, or a leaf `done` story, still needs a test (hard) — the
  exemption is not a blanket escape.

`story_order.py` prints an epic → children hierarchy alongside the sequencing
view. Under `github_master`, sub-issues are the master for `parent`; linking a
child issue to its parent on GitHub is an optional projection (best-effort, not
a gate).

## What the gate verifies

- **Hard (CI fails):** valid JSON object; `id`/`title`/`story`/`status`/
  `acceptance` present; `id` matches `STORY-NNNN` and is unique; `status` in the
  enum; every `acceptance[].text` non-empty; every `tests[]` path exists;
  `status: done` has ≥1 test; an `adr` link resolves to a file.
- **Best-effort:** an `in-progress`/`done` story with more acceptance criteria
  than mapped tests prints a note — the missing *mapping* is visible; semantic
  coverage stays a human judgement.
- **Ignored:** `*.example.json` seeds; unknown fields (cross-module forward-compat).

## Definition of Ready / Done

Not a new checkbox — a one-place view of the bar every story clears, each item
owned and enforced elsewhere. Use it to see the whole lifecycle at a glance.

**Ready to start:**
- a real user story (`story`) and gradeable acceptance (`acceptance`);
- the approach recorded (the plan, for Tier 3+);
- an issue link before code, for Tier 3+ (the `github-issues` module enforces it
  on the plan).

**Done:**
- every acceptance criterion maps a test (`tests`; mandatory rule "tests prove
  acceptance") — the registry gate requires ≥1 test for `status: done`;
- the independent review *attested* its independence (the review gate validates
  the attestation, not the run itself — `verification-independence.md`);
- a `done` story carries an issue link (the `github-issues` module makes this
  hard — for *every* done story, epic or leaf, unlike the test rule which an
  epic's children can cover) and its issue is `closed` (the `github-master`
  module checks this offline where GitHub is the source of truth);
- the registry, and any affected contract/parity SSOT, are updated.
